Let's also recall, ***what is a balance sheet?***

The **balance sheet** is a photo of the financial health of a firm. It presents what a firm owns (its assets), what a firm owes (its liabilities), and the difference between the two (the firm’s equity) at a given point in time. The balance sheet identity or equation can be determined as follows: 
$$
\begin{equation}
\text{Assets} = \text{Liabilities} + \text{Shareholders’ equity} 
\end{equation}
$$

Is important to say that both sides of the balance sheet present the same total since in the left part all assets are listed (current and fixed) and, in the right part, liabilities and equity are presented. It is perfectly balanced, hence its name. 

When two companies merge, the values of their balance sheets are combined, and usually added. Only when fair market values are different, the value added is the market value instead the book value.
